      <meta name="maintainer" content="tahlia.richardson@suse.com" its:translate="no"/>
      <meta name="architecture">
        <phrase>&x86-64;</phrase>
        <phrase>&power;</phrase>
        <phrase>&zseries;</phrase>
      </meta>
      <meta name="productname" its:translate="no">
        <productname version="&productnumber;" os="sleha">&productname;</productname>
      </meta>
      <meta name="title" its:translate="yes">Performing maintenance tasks on cluster nodes</meta>
      <meta name="description" its:translate="yes">How to minimize risk and resource downtime while making changes to one or more cluster nodes</meta>
      <meta name="social-descr" its:translate="yes">Minimize risk while maintaining cluster nodes</meta>
      <meta name="category" its:translate="no">
        <phrase>Administration</phrase>
      </meta>
      <meta name="task" its:translate="no">
        <phrase>Administration</phrase>
        <phrase>Clustering</phrase>
        <phrase>High Availability</phrase>
        <phrase>Maintenance</phrase>
      </meta>
      <meta name="series" its:translate="no">Products &amp; Solutions</meta>
      <dm:docmanager xmlns:dm="urn:x-suse:ns:docmanager">
        <dm:bugtracker>
          <dm:url>https://bugzilla.suse.com/enter_bug.cgi</dm:url>
          <dm:component>Documentation</dm:component>
          <dm:product>SUSE Linux Enterprise High Availability &productnumber;</dm:product>
          <dm:assignee>tahlia.richardson@suse.com</dm:assignee>
       </dm:bugtracker>
        <dm:translation>yes</dm:translation>
      </dm:docmanager>
      <abstract>
        <para>
          &ha; clusters require extra preparation steps before you can perform maintenance tasks,
          or you risk side effects such as resource failure, unsynchronized CIBs, or data loss.
          Use this workflow when making changes to the cluster nodes, such as hardware, software
          or firmware updates. This involves putting a node into standby mode and stopping the
          cluster services on just that node, then rebooting if required. To make changes to
          multiple nodes, repeat these steps on one node at a time.
        </para>
        <tip role="compact">
          <para>
            If this isn't the workflow you need, see <xref linkend="ha-maintenance-other-workflows"/>
            to choose the right one.
          </para>
        </tip>
        <important>
          <title>Maintenance window</title>
          <para>
            Preparing a node for maintenance only takes a few minutes. In this scenario, most
            resources don't require downtime because the cluster moves them to other nodes, but
            some resources might stop if constraints prevent them from moving. The resources
            will still be highly available because only one node at a time is offline.
            <!-- Alternative: "If the cluster has three or more nodes, the resources will still
            be highly available even while one of those nodes is offline." -->
          </para>
        </important>
      </abstract>
    </merge>
